04697nam a22005655i 9780226438955DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20082007ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226438955  a(DE-B1597)522680  a(OCoLC)1086468170  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aD802.F8bK5213 2008eb (Online) 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a940.54/86442221 aKitson, Simon, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Hunt for Nazi Spies :bFighting Espionage in Vichy France /cSimon Kitson. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2008] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (208 p.) :b2 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface to the English Language Edition -- tAcknowledgments -- tGlossary and Abbreviations -- tChronology of World War II France -- tIntroduction -- t1. Organizing German Espionage -- t2. Becoming a Spy -- t3. The Structures of French Counterespionage -- t4. Secret Service Ambiguities -- t5. Everyday Counterespionage -- t6. The Fate of the Spies -- t7. Understanding Vichy’s Policy -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom 1940 to 1942, French secret agents arrested more than two thousand spies working for the Germans and executed several dozen of them—all despite the Vichy government’s declared collaboration with the Third Reich. A previously untold chapter in the history of World War II, this duplicitous activity is the gripping subject of The Hunt for Nazi Spies, a tautly narrated chronicle of the Vichy regime’s attempts to maintain sovereignty while supporting its Nazi occupiers. Simon Kitson informs this remarkable story with findings from his investigation—the first by any historian—of thousands of Vichy documents seized in turn by the Nazis and the Soviets and returned to France only in the 1990s. His pioneering detective work uncovers a puzzling paradox: a French government that was hunting down left-wing activists and supporters of Charles de Gaulle’s Free French forces was also working to undermine the influence of German spies who were pursuing the same Gaullists and resisters. In light of this apparent contradiction, Kitson does not deny that Vichy France was committed to assisting the Nazi cause, but illuminates the complex agendas that characterized the collaboration and shows how it was possible to be both anti-German and anti-Gaullist. Combining nuanced conclusions with dramatic accounts of the lives of spies on both sides, The Hunt for Nazi Spies adds an important new dimension to our understanding of the French predicament under German occupation and the shadowy world of World War II espionage.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEspionage, GermanzFrancexHistoryy20th century. 0aSpieszGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xCollaborationistszFrance. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xSecret servicezFrance. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xSecret servicezGermany. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aespionage, national, socialist, party, holocaust, nazis, france, french, vichy, 1940s, 20th century, contemporary, modern, wwii, wartime, world war, occupation, regime, sovereignty, soviet, government, activist, activism, paradox, gaul, resister, resistance, germany, europe, european, collaborationist, counterespionage, detective, investigation.1 aTihanyi, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022643893140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226438955423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226438955/orig